.SH "Detailed Description"
.PP 

.SH "Unit tests"
.PP
The sources in this directory are unit test cases\&. Boost includes a unit testing framework, and since Bitcoin Core already uses Boost, it makes sense to simply use this framework rather than require developers to configure some other framework (we want as few impediments to creating unit tests as possible)\&.

.PP
The build system is set up to compile an executable called \fRtest_bitcoin\fP that runs all of the unit tests\&. The main source file for the test library is found in \fR\fButil/setup_common\&.cpp\fP\fP\&.

.PP
The examples in this document assume the build directory is named \fRbuild\fP\&. You'll need to adapt them if you named it differently\&.
.SS "Compiling/running unit tests"
Unit tests will be automatically compiled if dependencies were met during the generation of the Bitcoin Core build system and tests weren't explicitly disabled\&.

.PP
The unit tests can be run with \fRctest --test-dir build\fP, which includes unit tests from subtrees\&.

.PP
Run \fRbuild/bin/test_bitcoin --list_content\fP for the full list of tests\&.

.PP
To run the unit tests manually, launch \fRbuild/bin/test_bitcoin\fP\&. To recompile after a test file was modified, run \fRcmake --build build\fP and then run the test again\&. If you modify a non-test file, use \fRcmake --build build --target test_bitcoin\fP to recompile only what's needed to run the unit tests\&.

.PP
To add more unit tests, add \fR\fBBOOST_AUTO_TEST_CASE\fP\fP functions to the existing \&.cpp files in the \fRtest/\fP directory or add new \&.cpp files that implement new \fRBOOST_AUTO_TEST_SUITE\fP sections\&.

.PP
To run the GUI unit tests manually, launch \fRbuild/bin/test_bitcoin-qt\fP

.PP
To add more GUI unit tests, add them to the \fRsrc/qt/test/\fP directory and the \fR\fBsrc/qt/test/test_main\&.cpp\fP\fP file\&.
.SS "Running individual tests"
The \fRtest_bitcoin\fP runner accepts command line arguments from the Boost framework\&. To see the list of arguments that may be passed, run:

.PP
.PP
.nf
build/bin/test_bitcoin \-\-help
.fi
.PP

.PP
For example, to run only the tests in the \fRgetarg_tests\fP file, with full logging:

.PP
.PP
.nf
build/bin/test_bitcoin \-\-log_level=all \-\-run_test=getarg_tests
.fi
.PP

.PP
or

.PP
.PP
.nf
build/bin/test_bitcoin \-l all \-t getarg_tests
.fi
.PP

.PP
or to run only the doubledash test in \fRgetarg_tests\fP

.PP
.PP
.nf
build/bin/test_bitcoin \-\-run_test=getarg_tests/doubledash
.fi
.PP

.PP
The \fR--log_level=\fP (or \fR-l\fP) argument controls the verbosity of the test output\&.

.PP
The \fRtest_bitcoin\fP runner also accepts some of the command line arguments accepted by \fRbitcoind\fP\&. Use \fR--\fP to separate these sets of arguments:

.PP
.PP
.nf
build/bin/test_bitcoin \-\-log_level=all \-\-run_test=getarg_tests \-\- \-printtoconsole=1
.fi
.PP

.PP
The \fR-printtoconsole=1\fP after the two dashes sends debug logging, which normally goes only to \fRdebug\&.log\fP within the data directory, to the standard terminal output as well\&.

.PP
Running \fRtest_bitcoin\fP creates a temporary working (data) directory with a randomly generated pathname within \fRtest_common bitcoin/\fP, which in turn is within the system's temporary directory (see \fR\fRtemp_directory_path\fP\fP)\&. This data directory looks like a simplified form of the standard \fRbitcoind\fP data directory\&. Its content will vary depending on the test, but it will always have a \fRdebug\&.log\fP file, for example\&.

.PP
The location of the temporary data directory can be specified with the \fR-testdatadir\fP option\&. This can make debugging easier\&. The directory path used is the argument path appended with \fR/test_common bitcoin/<test-name>/datadir\fP\&. The directory path is created if necessary\&. Specifying this argument also causes the data directory not to be removed after the last test\&. This is useful for looking at what the test wrote to \fRdebug\&.log\fP after it completes, for example\&. (The directory is removed at the start of the next test run, so no leftover state is used\&.)

.PP
.PP
.nf
$ build/bin/test_bitcoin \-\-run_test=getarg_tests/doubledash \-\- \-testdatadir=/somewhere/mydatadir
Test directory (will not be deleted): "/somewhere/mydatadir/test_common bitcoin/getarg_tests/doubledash/datadir"
Running 1 test case\&.\&.\&.

*** No errors detected
$ ls \-l '/somewhere/mydatadir/test_common bitcoin/getarg_tests/doubledash/datadir'
total 8
drwxrwxr\-x 2 admin admin 4096 Nov 27 22:45 blocks
\-rw\-rw\-r\-\- 1 admin admin 1003 Nov 27 22:45 debug\&.log
.fi
.PP

.PP
If you run an entire test suite, such as \fR--run_test=getarg_tests\fP, or all the test suites (by not specifying \fR--run_test\fP), a separate directory will be created for each individual test\&.
.SS "Adding test cases"
To add a new unit test file to our test suite, you need to add the file to either \fRsrc/test/CMakeLists\&.txt\fP or \fRsrc/wallet/test/CMakeLists\&.txt\fP for wallet-related tests\&. The pattern is to create one test file for each class or source file for which you want to create unit tests\&. The file naming convention is \fR<source_filename>_tests\&.cpp\fP and such files should wrap their tests in a test suite called \fR<source_filename>_tests\fP\&. For an example of this pattern, see \fR\fBuint256_tests\&.cpp\fP\fP\&.
.SS "Logging and debugging in unit tests"
\fRctest --test-dir build\fP will write to the log file \fRbuild/Testing/Temporary/LastTest\&.log\fP\&. You can additionally use the \fR--output-on-failure\fP option to display logs of the failed tests automatically on failure\&. For running individual tests verbosely, refer to the section \fBabove\fP\&.

.PP
To write to logs from unit tests you need to use specific message methods provided by Boost\&. The simplest is \fRBOOST_TEST_MESSAGE\fP\&.

.PP
For debugging you can launch the \fRtest_bitcoin\fP executable with \fRgdb\fP or \fRlldb\fP and start debugging, just like you would with any other program:

.PP
.PP
.nf
gdb build/bin/test_bitcoin
.fi
.PP
.SS "Segmentation faults"
If you hit a segmentation fault during a test run, you can diagnose where the fault is happening by running \fRgdb \&./build/bin/test_bitcoin\fP and then using the \fRbt\fP command within gdb\&.

.PP
Another tool that can be used to resolve segmentation faults is \fRvalgrind\fP\&.

.PP
If for whatever reason you want to produce a core dump file for this fault, you can do that as well\&. By default, the boost test runner will intercept system errors and not produce a core file\&. To bypass this, add \fR--catch_system_errors=no\fP to the \fRtest_bitcoin\fP arguments and ensure that your ulimits are set properly (e\&.g\&. \fRulimit -c unlimited\fP)\&.

.PP
Running the tests and hitting a segmentation fault should now produce a file called \fRcore\fP (on Linux platforms, the file name will likely depend on the contents of \fR/proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\fP)\&.

.PP
You can then explore the core dump using 
.PP
.nf
gdb build/bin/test_bitcoin core

(gdb) bt  # produce a backtrace for where a segfault occurred

.fi
.PP
 
